The social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region is recognized as an electronic means of payment.
The changes provide for the preservation of travel privileges in public passenger transport.
Since September 24, the procedure for organizing preferential travel of citizens using the social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region has been changing.
According to the press service of the Russian government in the Ivanovo region, the changes provide for the preservation of travel privileges in public passenger transport and bring the scheme of mutual settlements on the social card in accordance with the requirements of Federal Law No. 161 of the Federal Law "On the National Payment System".
At the same time, the social card of a resident of the Ivanovo region is recognized as an electronic means of payment.
Accordingly, the conditions of its application are changing.
So, the replenishment limit is now set not in travel, as before, but in the amount of money, with the preservation of winter and summer periods - in winter no more than 400 rubles, in summer - no more than 800 rubles for the current month.
Now the holders of the social card on the receipts issued in transport will need to track not the number of remaining trips, but the balance of funds.
The cost of preferential travel for citizens will be 1/2 of the tariff applicable to the carrier.
The remaining half of the cost of travel is reimbursed by the regional budget.
The schedule of replenishment of the social card in cash remains the same - in the period from the 24th of the previous month to the 23rd of the current month.
The new order of travel on the social card will have a number of advantages.
Thus, it becomes possible to keep a detailed record of spending money on a social card with an accuracy of kopecks.
In addition, it is possible to return credited but unspent funds.
We also add that the scheme of settlements with carriers becomes transparent, since now half of the cost of travel is paid by the citizen, and exactly the same amount reimburses the carrier the budget.
No commission will be charged when depositing money on the card.
In turn, Vasily Silkin, Deputy Head of the Department of Road Economy and Transport of the Ivanovo region, said that in 2014 more than 33 million trips using a social card were made in the region, in 2015 - almost 25 million trips.
In the regional budget for the provision of preferential travel of citizens using the social card provided for more than 470 million rubles.
As of September 1, the amount of compensation for these purposes amounted to more than 312 million rubles.
During a 911 call, a teacher confesses to the murder of a friend
During a 911 call, Shannon Lamb, a high school teacher, told police that he had shot his girlfriend and that they needed staff to come to their home.
Lamb said there was a "dog" in the house who was alive but probably upset, and said the family's contacts could be found on her phone.
Inside the house, police found the body of Amy Prentiss and a note carelessly written by hand on a white sheet of linden paper: “I’m sorry, I would like to bring everything back, I loved Amy, and she is the only woman who has ever loved me,” the note reads, according to organ officials signed by Lamb.
Nothing indicated that Lamb, who ran two online courses at Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, had by then traveled 300 miles to the university campus, where police believe he shot and killed respected history professor Ethan Schmidt on the doorstep of his office.
Delta State Police Chief Lynne Baford said university officials learned of the shooting at 10:18 a.m.
He reported that Lamb made that truthful 911 call shortly after.
By the end of the day, the victims will be one more: Lamb committed suicide as soon as the police surrounded him.
The day after the shooting at the school forced students and teachers to hide behind locked doors, officials were still trying to piece together Lamb’s motivations.
The information shared by investigators in both ends of the state, as well as students and staff who knew him, helped to make a portrait of a talented, but perhaps worried teacher.
The students said they were looking forward to his classes.
Police in Gauthier, where Prentiss died, said he was not charged with violence or criminal charges.
Schmidt himself included Lamb in a book he wrote in which he expressed appreciation for the "beautiful people" he had crossed paths with in his teaching life.
They both taught at the Faculty of Social Sciences and History, which has 17 faculty members, and many students attended lectures of both.
At the same time, there were some prerequisites for the emergence of problems.
One student who spoke well of Lamb, Brandon Beavers, reported that he also seemed anxious and nervous, "as if something was wrong with him."
Another student, Michael Sykes, reported that Lamb told him at the end of the 2014-15 school year about how he struggled with stress.
Earlier, Lamb asked Delta State University to grant him sick leave, saying that he has some health problems.
This year he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes in university admissions rules meant that Lamb's doctorate, which he had worked so hard for, would not have guaranteed him an automatic teaching position.
University President William LaForge said he knew nothing about the conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but "it's obvious that Mr. Lamb had something on his mind."
These are questions that Lamb will no longer be able to answer.
Police attacked Lamb's trail after he escaped from campus as he was heading back to Mississippi from Arkansas.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb shot himself with a 38-caliber detachable pistol in the back yard of the house, one mile south of his parents' home in suburban Greenville, Mississippi, Washington County coroner Metal Johnson said.
His engine-powered car was still on the driveway.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb came to this house, although, according to Johnson, she believes that he knew the people living in it.
Lamb grew up in those parts.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3,500 students in a city of about 12,000, in 2009 and has taught geography and pedagogy.
He received his Doctor of Pedagogical Sciences degree in the spring of the same year.
One of Lamb’s longtime friends described him as a smart, charismatic, and fun person.
Carla Hayrston said she was 15 and Lamba was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
She and her friends were in high school, and he was a cool older guy who had been trying to teach her how to play guitar for years.
In those years, he was successful with women.
All the girls were melting when he was around,” says Hayrston, now 40, who lives in Jackson, a suburb of Brandon.
Lamb and Prentiss had apparently been dating for some time.
During a 911 call, Lamb said, "I killed my wife," but there is no record of their marriage registration.
The couple had a dog named Lightning, who lived with them in Gauthier in a brick house, the other side of which overlooks the canal.
Police say the dog is fine.
Prentiss’s ex-husband, Sean O’Steen, revealed that they divorced 15 years ago, but remained friends, and that they have a daughter who is now 19 years old.
"She's completely depressed," O'Stin said of her daughter.
She and her mother were good friends.
O'Steen said he had not met Lamb, but heard from his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and played blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail both performed at the same summer festival three years ago.
Then they played together from time to time at concerts.
O'Steen said his daughter writes music and sings.
Prentice was a nurse and worked online for various companies.
Mike Shaffer, a bartender and part-time entertainment coordinator at the dimly lit The Julep Room bar in the suburb of Gauthier, said the last time he saw Lamb and Prentiss was on the evening of September 5, when Lamb finished playing guitar and mouth harmonica for a few visitors.
Nothing suspicious was observed.
“Just a happy couple,” he said.
We were having fun and making fun of each other.
I mean, they were both very witty.
Schmidt, the deceased teacher, conducted seminars for freshmen and specialized in Native American and colonial American history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English teacher at the same institution.
He was married and had three young children.
He attended Kansas State University in Emporia and was president of the student fraternity and student self-government.
On the campus of Delta State University in Cleveland on Tuesday evening, about 900 people, including university faculty, staff, students and community members, participated in a candlelight memorial ceremony.
