8 Poll Results That Show Donald Trump Isn't Joking
Some have tried to label him a provocateur.
Others dismissed him as a joke.
Some people want a scandal.
But no matter how hard some Republicans try to shake the high position of Donald Trump in the results of polls, they have failed (so far).
Ten of the last 11 national polls have demonstrated Donald Trump’s double-digit advantage, and some are starting to ask seriously what this means for a real estate mogul in terms of chances of getting a nomination.
Of course, this is just the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this means that Trump has a chance to be nominated by the Republican Party.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry was inferior to the growing popularity of Herman Kane, none of whom won one state in the nomination process.
And there are many reasons why he would fight in a general election.
But outside groups such as Jeb Bush’s Political Action Super Committee and the economic conservative Growth Club recognize Trump’s unremitting power and are beginning to pull out their dollars to tip him over.
Here are some survey numbers that suggest a real estate mogul isn’t just an intermediate phase:
The ratings of sympathy for trump turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a survey at Monmouth University showed that only two out of 10 Republicans were positive about this real estate mogul.
By mid-July, it was 40 percent.
In early August, it was 52 percent.
Six out of 10 Republicans now have a positive view of Donald Trump.
About three in 10 say they have a negative opinion.
And all these indicators gain the upper hand in the initial stages.
A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found that 60 percent of Republicans there are positive about Trump.
Two-thirds of those who voted for the GOP would accept Trump as a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they were either “excited” or “satisfied” if Trump became a candidate.
Only two out of 10 say they would be "disappointed" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson generates about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent say they would be “excited” against 40 percent of those who say the same about Trump).
Next in terms of excitement?
Marco Rubio, who has only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republicans say they would be “unsatisfied” or “disappointed” if establishment favorite Jeb Bush became a candidate.
Most Republicans don’t see Trump’s temperament as a problem.
While Trump is widely criticized for his bragging and insults, 52 percent of Republican-leaning voters across the country think the tycoon has the right temperament to be president, according to an ABC News/Washington post poll conducted Monday.
The same figure appears at the country’s first closed meeting in Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he’s the same person who could be the top commander, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he’s not the type of person who can be effective in office, and nearly six in 10 independent voters say his temperament isn’t right for the White House, according to ABC/Post reports.
Republican voters are getting used to this idea.
When they put on their hats of connoisseurs, Republican voters think Trump is serious.
Asked who was the most likely winner in the GOP nomination, four out of 10 said Trump was the favorite, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That’s no longer the case when four out of 10 bet on Jeb Bush at the end of July.
Full disclosure: GOP voters didn’t have the right magic crystal before.
At the same time, in the last cycle, four out of 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry as the most likely candidate, while only 28 percent supported a possible candidate, Mitt Romney.
However, this shows that many GOP voters see Trump’s campaign as compelling.
Even if Republicans rallied around another candidate, Trump is still ahead of everyone else.
Some pundits point out that such a spread is likely to play to Trump’s advantage, and at the same time, Trump’s supporters are evenly distributed among the supporting more than a dozen other candidates.
But a poll conducted by Monmouth University in early September shows that in a hypothetical one-on-one contest between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always gets majority support.
He is ahead of Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and finally Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie by 33 points.
He's got a draw with Ted Cruz.
Is he the only candidate who can get away with it?
Ben Carson overtook the businessman by as many as 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one competition.
Just over half of Donald Trump’s supporters say they have changed their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll conducted on Tuesday shows that only more than half of voters supporting Trump say they are confident in their votes.
Obviously, a lot can happen and change the situation, and no one can really say that he will never change his mind.
46% say they leave the door open for other candidates.
Still, Trump’s most intense competition so far is with fellow outsider neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who say they’ve changed their minds are likely to pick Trump.
Six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Since Donald Trump called Mexican immigrants “rapists” in his campaign opening speech two months ago, the topic of immigration has become the most relevant in conversations in 2016.
Some worry that Trump’s posturing will alienate key Latino voters from the Republican party and prevent rebranding.
But according to an ABC/Post poll conducted Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So as long as immigration continues to attract attention, it looks like Donald Trump will remain in the same position.
Disappointment from the government is gaining momentum.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson now count on the support of about half of Republican voters, mainly because of their status as outsiders.
In a new ABC/Post poll on Monday, 10 Republicans said they wanted a political outsider rather than someone with government experience.
And they're also offended at Washington.
The Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa, conducted two weeks ago, shows that three out of four Republicans in Iowa are disappointed with Republican activity in Congress, with 54 percent "unsatisfied" and 21 percent "furious."
