Metcash launches bottom-up campaign to fight Aldi’s onslaught
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from the onslaught of Aldi in South Australia and Western Australia.
A wholesale food supplier has launched a grassroots campaign to protect the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in light of Aldi’s upcoming $700 million infusion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two wholesale warehouses and the first of 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening relationships with local food suppliers and promoting the IGA brand through marketing in leading media and social media and at events like the Adelaide Show.
The campaign is joined by IGA retailers and suppliers, such as ice cream maker Simmo's of Dunsboro, which offers tastings at IGA stores, and store owners selling discounted regular customers tickets to South Australian Football League matches.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details of its protection strategy on September 29, the day that this wholesaler of food, spirits and household goods will hold its annual investor strategy day.
In South Australia and Western Australia, IGA stores account for almost 30% of all Metcash stores and show higher profitability than the Metcash IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South and Western Australia are known to follow the usual routes, so the market here is more favorable for IGA retailers than in the states of New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 percent in the South and 24 percent in WA, compared to about 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will take 5 percent of the food market in these two states within 12 months of opening its first stores, taking sales from all players present, but mainly from independent retailers.
In a report published this week, Tom Kirat, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, believes that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year, and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
The forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, achieving sales of $500 million and $600 million in these markets, respectively.
The loss of revenue and sales of food products at a high level of constant costs Metcash can cost the company about 13 million revenues before paying interest and taxes, said Mr. Kirat.
