What happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates?
There will be an increase in rates, and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise, and the economy will fall into recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will take before the attack, and how long it will last.
In economics, history explains little about time.
The recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike and for as much as 86 months.
The rigidity of the Federal Reserve in raising rates often, though not always, determines the response of the economy and financial assets.
Therefore, the administration of the US Central Bank is so insistent that investors should not focus on when it will start raising rates, but on how long it will take to adapt.
In fact, there are many variables in the game.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the fuss around raising rates turns out to be exaggerated.
“The Federal Reserve’s first rate hike with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal of the end of the ‘cheap money’ era,” Julian Jessop, chief international economist at Capital Economics, said in a comment to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to more normal, but still low, levels to be the seismic momentum that many fear.
This does not mean, however, that there will be no consequences.
Here’s a look at how some areas of the economy might have reacted depending on historical trends:
As the market has seen over the past month or so, waiting for rates to rise can lead to volatility for a while.
With an increase in the rate, however, the consequences are usually not as dramatic.
“It doesn’t look like stock returns have slowed down 12-24 months after the first jump, which, again, probably reflects a delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of the results of rate hikes by the Federal Reserve.
More specifically, the market has been changing dramatically over the past 35 years — about 14 percent — toward higher rates, staying fairly flat for 250 days afterward (average 2.6 percent growth), then returning to normal after 500 days, with an average return of 14.4 percent over the past six cycles, according to a recent analysis conducted by Bob Doll, chief stock trading strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, a public.
Deutsche says that the outcome for securities tends not to become more pronounced immediately at the stage of raising rates, and earnings from stocks begin to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often contribute to them.
In this case, the Federal Reserve is put in conditions that did not exist before and can accelerate the recession.
Basically, gross domestic product will be at almost its lowest point for the entire existence of the increased rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 cases of rate hikes since 1950, only twice the nominal annual GDP was below 4.5 percent.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will last long, even though it held at just 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to Atlanta Fed data.
Raising rates on such an unstable economic background can be risky and raises the question "whether this time will be different," Deutsche said.
Market participants are preparing to raise rates by the Federal Reserve all year round, with their eyes fixed on the meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve rate hikes at this meeting, futures trading suggests only a 25 percent probability.
"In our study since 1950, all rate hike cycles to date have been in a super-cycle of increasing fiscal leverage with GDP overlapping the peaks preceding recession very quickly after the recovery began," the report said.
By contrast, it was an extremely slow recovery from the worst recession in the chosen period.
The current cycle is the longest the Federal Reserve has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, a total of 74 months and not yet over.
Fixed income has also become volatile while the market expects rates to rise, and this scenario is somewhat similar to the one implemented for stocks.
The fundamental difference is that for bonds, the effect will come faster than for stocks, when the Federal system changes its strategic course.
In the case of bonds, it appears that the yield changes vector immediately after the first rate increase/decrease in the cycle.
At the end of the rate hike cycle, bond yields fall immediately,” Deutsche said.
Strategy experts at Charles Schwab believe that raising rates will cause long-term and short-term bond yields to converge, making the curve flatter.
High-yield bonds often behave better in such a climate, although “we are still wary of fluctuations in yields,” says Katie Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab.
It is interesting that Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the expected results of the policy of the Federal system.
“In addition to strengthening the dollar and falling inflation expectations, there are signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Interest rates on short-term loans have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have expanded, volatility has increased - all the characteristics of the market with the tightening of the policy of the Federal system.
In general, companies doing their main business in the United States will benefit from higher interest rates, and local products will become more attractive.
International companies with many debts will be in a worse position, as the growing dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market space, and their debt more expensive in the financial space.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks show above-market performance within three months of initial rate hikes,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for clients.
Firms with a stable financial position outperformed those with an unstable position as a result of each rate increase in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital returns, as well as stocks with low volatility, also performed better than low-quality stocks by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt will be a big question.
Companies with high floating-rate debt will lose the most, according to Goldman.
In addition to purely exchange transactions, consumers will benefit from a rising dollar.
Depositors could see gains through higher returns as well, although experts differ on how fast this will happen.
