Vangelis Meymarakis: “Europe wants to help us”
Vangelis Meimarakis has been part of center-right governments for a number of years, leading, according to the left, the country to a financial crisis.
Now that he is interim leader of the New Democracy party, he is challenging Tsipras.
A few days before the election, he met with a Euronews journalist.
Euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronews: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat, losing to the Syriza coalition, but now, judging by polls, New Democracy has equaled it in popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Meymarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot last January.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and prospects for economic growth.
Now the country again has a budget deficit and a high unemployment rate.
Investors left because Mr. Tsipras drove them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what was promised with what actually happened.
Everyday life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation was improving, and this applied to the majority of Greek citizens.
Euronews: But you say that if you win the elections, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
Vangelis Meimarakis: The fact is that, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
It is no coincidence that in all other countries where rescue programs have been or are still in operation, political forces and all ruling parties have come together to implement the program by which they have reached agreement, without giving up their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party voted in favour of the agreement between Mr Tsipras and the country’s creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you honor that agreement, or will you try to change it, at least in part?
Vangelis Meimarakis: In fact, we voted for the movement of Greece along the European path, because we are well aware of the disastrous consequences of the country’s exit from the EU.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, a Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All this would have been lost if there had not been a treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of Mr Tsipras’s handling of the negotiations.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government during its first year in power wants to restore order, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then, I am sure, all the commitments that have been made that cannot be fulfilled due to the fact that they lead to a recession can be renegotiated, but only after a certain time.
It would be a mistake to believe that in the first year of the new agreement we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect full implementation of the agreement.
If we are to regain their trust, we must continue the privatization, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed upon, while continuing to take advantage of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the negotiations, the Tsipras government did not present any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we found out by discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give you an example related to farmers’ income.
We explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income, and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that the ministers of Tsipras never talked about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were unprepared and poorly informed, and therefore failed to negotiate and conclude a failed agreement.
Euronews: If you win the election, you will soon find yourself at the same table with Mr. Juncker, Hollande, Ms. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them be different from what your predecessor, Antonis Samaras, told them?
Vangelis Meimarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that until the end of 2014 we tried to best implement the 2012 agreement, bypassing the sharp corners in it.
We have pushed reform forward.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in emergency circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price that satisfied the Greek government.
I was the Speaker of Parliament at the time, and I was able to agree on the views of the three parliamentary groups that were then the government majority.
And despite their serious ideological differences on key bills, we had a functioning parliament, and this in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations held outside.
And we managed to bring the country to a normal situation that would have continued to improve if the process had not been interrupted by the early general elections that resulted from the December presidential election.
Euronews: In recent weeks, there has been a massive influx of refugees across Greece.
What do you think about this situation, and about the reaction of European countries to which these people aspire?
Vangelis Meimarakis: The refugee crisis is a time bomb that we have to deal with after winning the election.
And the reason is that the Syriza government did not act in this situation as it should.
In such matters, you should act ahead, because if the problem overtakes you, then only emergency measures remain.
And we are in that situation now.
Even the provisional government that succeeded SYRIZA did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am sure that these actions of the interim government, which is provided with valuable assistance by the president of the republic, who called for an EU summit, will allow us to find a solution.
We need to see how many refugees will be able to leave the country, and note that refugees are not illegal immigrants.
These are the victims of the war in Syria, the victims of some extraordinary events that happened to them.
This issue has a deeply humanitarian aspect, and we will adhere to the position that European politicians must adopt in this new situation.
The decision should be taken at the EU summit, and the United Nations should be involved.
We also need better coordination, better border controls and refugee reception centres.
We must also make effective use of the economic assistance that we receive from the EU in order to be able to cope with this urgent problem.
Euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you.
