Does David Cameron know anything else about Lorax?
Each parent learns one thing very quickly: if your child likes a book, it will take a little time before you know it almost by heart.
Unless you're David Cameron.
In response to a question from a representative of a holiday company about his favorite children’s book, the Prime Minister chose Lorax, an environmental fairy tale written by Dr. Seuss in 1971.
It was a difficult choice, Cameron wrote in a comment posted on the SuperCamps website, and continues: "This fun, touching, unusual story with a strong message I love to read to my children because it always reveals some image or message that we miss."
And all would be well, except for the last paragraph, in which Cameron is supposed to retell the contents of the book, but in fact tells the plot of the film of the same name, shot in 2012, with new characters and details added to diversify the rather short original narrative.
“In the high-walled town of Vsemusville, where there was no greenery and even air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of her dreams, by fulfilling her desire to see a real tree,” we read in the text a description of a love story unknown to Dr. Seuss (real name Theodore Seus Geisel), who died in 1991.
If it doesn’t look suspicious enough, Cameron’s text reads almost like a summary of the plot of the movie “Lorax”, posted on the Internet Movie Database: “In the high-walled city of Vsemunouville, where everything was artificial and even air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey - the girls of his dreams.”
It seems unlikely that Cameron, admittedly an active parent, is so unfamiliar with the contents of a book in which an unnamed boy learns about how a greedy tree cutter and all-girl binder, Nakhodkins, is destroying the environment, despite the protests of Lorax (whose name is taken out in the title of the book) - a funny creature with a mustache who "speaks on behalf of the trees."
Most likely, such a simple PR task was assigned to the performer who never read a child a book about Lorax 20 times in a row.
A Downing Street spokeswoman said the text was allegedly obtained from Cameron's office in the constituency.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was received from Cameron's headquarters, but no further comment followed.
