Experts criticize Public Health England review of e-cigarettes
The government-funded agency’s claims that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking were made at a meeting of 12 people, some of whom are related to the tobacco industry, the researchers reported.
Experts published in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) in conjunction with Lancet criticized the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
The PHE released an important report last month, calling it a “comprehensive review of the evidence.”
But some researchers have questioned the reliability of the data and pointed to the connection of some experts with the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the medical journal Lancet last month criticized the “extremely shaky argument” on which PHE built its main conclusion.
In a BMJ paper, two other researchers wondered whether these claims have “solid or flimsy grounds.”
Martin McKee, a lecturer in European health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capwell, a lecturer in clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: “The fundamental principle of health is that rules should be based on evidence of efficacy.”
According to them, the public expects PHE’s claims that “the current best estimate shows that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than tobacco” to be based on detailed analysis of evidence and modeling.
In fact, this is derived from a single meeting of 12 people gathered to develop a multi-criteria decision analysis model in order to summarize their views on the harms associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting are summarized in a scientific publication.
McKee and Capewell reported that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO was reported to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco for an independent study.
He also confirmed the BAT certifications in the health sector in a sustainability report.
One in 12 people at the meeting announced funding from the e-cigarette maker, without mentioning the funding it had reportedly previously received from the tobacco company Philip Morris.
A reasonable explanation for the selection of council members has not been provided, but among them there are several prominent proponents of e-cigarettes, some of whom have also claimed industry funding in the publication.
It is not known whether other participants of the meeting have experience in managing tobacco business.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco department at PHE.
The research paper, published by the group, "exquisitely agrees" that there is a lack of "strong evidence of harmful effects of most products by most criteria," McKee and Capwell wrote.
However, none of these links and limitations were addressed in the PHE report.
