"Sonogenetics" allows you to control brain cells using sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have brought out worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound pulses that are too high for the human ear to hear.
The pulses have an impact by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
Next Next post: Researchers Control Brain Activity with Light
The scientists said that the worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called “sonogenetics”, the essence of which is to use ultrasound to excite certain cells of the brain, heart and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Srikanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Hoya, California, told the Guardian that the technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are sent to the human brain and used to treat Parkinson’s disease.
Nematode worms usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to respond when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate into the body of worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect structures called "TRP-4 ion channels" found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications to the worms, so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the use of ultrasound to affect modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into worm organisms, activating modified motor neurons.
The technique is similar to that used in optogenetics, a new direction that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off with light pulses.
Chalasani argues that, compared to this technique, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired area of the brain through the optical fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves freely pass through the tissues of the body, so for their delivery it is not necessary to pass inside the cranial box.
"We believe that for the treatment of certain neurological diseases in clinical settings, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses can temporarily make human neurons sensitive to ultrasound," Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
