Kiev broke the atomic union.
Kiev has officially formalized Ukraine’s refusal to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday on the second attempt still voted to terminate the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but it was not possible to start implementing the project.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law terminating an agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth block at the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The bill was introduced by the government only with the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the necessary minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted in favor of the draft.
The Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant, laid under the USSR, was originally designed to have four power units of 1 GW with VVER reactors, but managed to build only two.
Negotiations with Moscow on completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2011-2012, the Rada adopted relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the Russian side would have to build blocks on credit, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the ensuing cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to wind down relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing a refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant and on the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations have remained is the purchase of fuel in the Russian Federation for the existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants (provided about half of the electricity generation in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NNEGC Energoatom has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
Plans for the completion of the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been definitively abandoned: back in 2014, negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS were announced in Kiev.
