At the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve officials will spend two days this week at a 27-foot table made of Honduran mahogany, deciding whether it’s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the richly decorated meeting room, two stories high, a wall image of the United States will hang over them.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the country’s economic interests above all others.
The Central Bank received a double order from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and keep stable prices here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal system have acknowledged that there is a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And that third assignment may prove to be an unknown factor in Thursday’s near-predicted decision whether the U.S. economy is poised to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Even though most data shows robust economic growth, recent turmoil in global financial markets could keep already cautious Federal System executives from adding volatility by raising the base federal funds rate — even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“It is clear that the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important consideration,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further,” she said.
There is no consensus on what will be done in the Federal Reserve, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
Roughly half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted interest rate increases this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal system to refrain from doing so, with the key indicator only showing a roughly 30 percent chance of a rapid recovery.
This could cause the stock market to fall if the Federal system raises the rate, provided that those who make the decisions do not soften the blow with the promise that the next increase will not be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones index climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rise was triggered by expectations that policy makers of the Federal System would leave the bet this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be a surprise if the federal system raises rates at this point in time,” he said.
If the Federal Reserve Board does that, “they’ll have to go a long way in approving their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that raising the rate could calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the federal system appeared to be inclined to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in slowly tightening financial conditions, which could confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been steady this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest level in more than seven years, and almost at what the federal system considers full employment.
Wage growth shows signs of acceleration.
And, although inflation continues to be below the central bank’s target of 2%, the Federal system’s leadership said the key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy “can and needs higher rates, given the shrinking labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones average for industrial stocks fell as much as 16% from a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could hamper global growth.
The market regained some ground this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10% below the high May value.
For the management of the Federal Reserve, the market disturbance further complicates the difficult calculations of the term for raising the interest rate.
“In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, they would be tightening the screws at this meeting,” said Steven D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the Federal Reserve.
Now, according to his forecasts, they will wait at least a month to gain more control over the consequences.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the implications might be for the U.S. economy, and they have little reliable data since the recent events in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not a major concern of the Federal system, and it should not be taken into account technically when making these decisions.
But essentially, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s financial power.
The central bank’s influence has been enormous in recent years.
Just a hint from then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could “stun” its monetary expansion has caused turmoil in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, it would be expected that Federal Reserve officials would not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is “more of an art than a science,” said Zachary Carabell, head of Envestnet Inc., a company that deals with global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Lucker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "there have been instances in the history of the Federal Reserve System of overreaction to financial market movements that do not seem to be related to economic principles."
Lacker, a voting member of the influential Federal Open Market Committee who insisted on raising the rate, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia has caused the Federal System to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the limited identifiable implications for U.S. growth,” Lucker said.
A year later, the leaders of the Federal system canceled these reductions.
The Federal Reserve should put stability first only in times of major crises, such as the 2008 market crash,” said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the interest rate committee at Bank of England.
The last panic did not come close to this level, he said.
“You certainly wouldn’t want to be in a situation where you’re scared of rising rates because markets are in turmoil,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for World Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don’t think they should be ahead of the curve.
