Four killed when police opened fire with rubber bullets on protesters in Nepal
Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal when police began firing rubber bullets at a crowd protesting the country's proposed new constitution, an official said on Wednesday.
The violence occurred Tuesday evening in Rupandei County, about 175 miles west of Kathmandu, the country's capital.
Bishnu Prasad Dakal, the head of the district police, reported that more than 1,000 protesters gathered outside one of the police stations, some throwing stones and incendiary bombs.
Mr. Dakal reported that police officers used tear gas and then fired into the air before firing rubber bullets.
Twenty police officers and five civilians were injured, he said.
It is unclear why rubber bullets, which are known to kill, but have traditionally been used as a less lethal alternative, have caused such a high mortality rate.
The clash was the latest in weeks of violent protests in southern, flat Nepal, where representatives of the Madizi people say the new provinces formed under the new constitution will reduce their political influence.
Protests also took place in western Nepal, among Taroo citizens who want to have their own state.
At least 40 people, including eleven police officers, have been killed in violent clashes since 10 days ago.
In August, when the four main political parties signed an agreement to divide the country into provinces, it was a decisive step towards a new constitution, but a highly controversial issue in Nepal, which was centrally administered for several centuries.
Work on a new constitution has been underway since 2008, but lawmakers have accelerated the process following a devastating earthquake that killed thousands in April.
Lawmakers voted for articles of the draft constitution in Kathmandu this week, and officials said the new chapter would be signed by Sunday.
