Diabetics with low obesity may be helped by obesity surgery
The beneficial effect after obesity surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say that diabetics with low obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive nonsurgical treatment.
“Mortality statistics don’t show up right away,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in obesity surgery who wrote about the new study in the JAMA Surgery editor’s column.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses a variety of techniques to reduce stomach size.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of organizations to absorb food.
Bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes over several years, but the main studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal at a value of 18.5 to 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or above indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0-Dv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass surgery and sleeve gastrectomy — with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with low obesity.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, BMI in those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and in part - 28%.
In the group receiving medication, for comparison, only 1% had a complete cure for diabetes, and only about 2% had a partial cure.
In addition, indicators of blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors state.
The researchers also monitored hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers wrote.
After surgery, average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, at about 8%.
But better glycemic control scores, reflected by good hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce the mortality rate over five years, according to study leader Dr Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of the two types of surgical treatment.
In the fifth year, compared to the group that received the sleeve gastrectomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was also closer to complete remission of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of the surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone from the College of Medicine in Phoenix, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study of obese people who chose bariatric intervention, the likelihood of dying over 15 years was about 29% lower compared to the group that used more traditional methods.
Despite the fact that the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this encourages people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in such a procedure.
“The report is very important here because it claims that such surgery is safe in a group with a low BMI, where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease,” she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient’s BMI falls in the range between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ve been waiting too long to get people to take this seriously,” she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse it.
