But whether any hotel ordered a similar procedure from regional enterprises, Smolny by an amazing coincidence is unknown.
That is, there may be more that have been classified, but no one knows about it.
"For the last six months, hotels have not been very eager to undergo classification," Ekaterina Shadskaya, director of the North-West branch of the Russian Union of Travel Industry, admitted.
This is due to the high season, during which hoteliers earn the most money and do not want to do other things.
Another reason is the budgets in which the costs of inspections were not laid down, while the procedure can cost the hotel depending on the status from 30 to 100 thousand rubles or more.
But still recently, hotel managers have intensified and began to apply for classification, assured Shadskaya.
Hotels have until July 1, 2016, otherwise they will not only pay a fine, but also not get the right to work at the World Cup.
It is already known that, depending on the star, a fixed fee will be developed for a hotel room during the tournament.
Formulas for which the cost will be calculated will be published next year.
This is done in order to prevent the rise in prices by 200-300%, as it happens, for example, during the St. Petersburg Economic Forum.
It is necessary to have a conscience and not to allow an increase of two or three times, but also hotels need to be allowed to earn money.
"I think the growth will be up to 50%," - said the President of the Russian hotel Association Gennady Lamshin.
In turn, Vadim Vladimirov is not sure that price fixing corresponds to the understanding of the market economy.
I do not know how far this fits into the framework of economic theory, but I hope that this measure is justified.
“It’s better than a runaway trip,” he said.
It is unclear what will happen to the popular cheap hostels.
Deputies of the state Duma introduced a bill according to which hostels should be banned in residential buildings.
We hope that this law will not be adopted or will not concern St. Petersburg.
“We will defend the view that hostels should be preserved,” Nana Gwachia said.
However, according to her, the owners of mini-hotels in any case should be ready to tighten the Housing Code.
If the State Duma does approve the bill, then about 80% of hostels will close in St. Petersburg, and at the moment there are 1.5 thousand rooms in them.
According to the president of the Federation of restaurateurs and hoteliers of the North-West Leonid Garbar, in St. Petersburg there is a lack of two- and three-star hotels, which are in demand by football fans, but there is a skew in the direction of hotels with four and five stars.
This state of affairs is similar to the situation when “75,000 VIPs sit in an 80,000-strong stadium.”
This can be fixed by mini-hotels.
The expert considers their possible ban to be "idiotism": "It seems strange to me that some people can live in apartments, but for some reason visitors can not."
If the hostel is used as a hostel, then I agree that this is wrong.
But if it’s like a hotel that guests come to for a short period of time, then why not?
Mini-hotels are at risk of missing the World Cup because of their slowness.
Hundreds of small hotels simply do not have time to pass the classification, and the hole dig itself.
By the summer of 2016, all hotels in the city will be ordering work.
“Companies that can carry out this procedure are not so many, so they will refuse less paid orders from the mini-hotel, and will choose those that are more expensive,” said Gennady Lamshin, adding that in a number of cities, for example, Moscow and Volgograd, the indicators of passed inspections at the moment are much higher than in St. Petersburg.
The reason for the St. Petersburg delay is due to the constant changes in the tourist block of the government, which does not contribute to coordinated work.
According to experts, if there are not enough St. Petersburg hotels, that will most likely have to pay attention to regional hotels and holiday homes.
Following the example of the celebration of the 300th anniversary of St. Petersburg, the river fleet can be mobilized to the city, that is, guests of the tournament will be able to live in cabins.
In addition, many fans are prepared to come in vans in which you can spend the night.
“The main thing is not to set up so many hotels that later they are empty,” Gennady Lamshin is sure.
Also very popular during the football championship will enjoy rental housing.
Most likely, a reserve of rented apartments will be created in the city.
Rental rates will increase by 10-30%.
"From the obvious - the first to leave housing near the stadium," - said the Agency for development and real estate research specialist Larisa Bragina.
Moreover, the rental price may not return to the same level after the championship, especially in the sleeping areas.
This will be facilitated by the construction of new transport interchanges on the outskirts of the city, she stressed.
Do not forget about the human qualities of citizens.
For example, Leonid Garbar is sure that St. Petersburg has always been a hospitable city, in which people not only suggest the way, but can also conduct a mini-excursion.
There are complications.
In 1970, my father met a family from Murmansk in the yard - a father, a mother and two children.
They had nowhere to sleep: it was difficult at that time with hotels, it was difficult to sleep at the station.
