"It's impossible for everyone to come to Europe" - Dalai Lama - RT News
Europe cannot accept all refugees, the Dalai Lama said, adding that the real solution to the current refugee crisis lies in the Middle East.
The leader of Tibetan Buddhists called for an end to violence in the countries that are the birthplace of refugees.
The Dalai Lama addressed the ongoing refugee crisis in a speech at the opening of the Dalai Lama’s Ethics Research Centre in Oxford at the beginning of his 10-day visit to the UK.
He said that in the circumstances, the interests of humanity should be above the interests of individual countries or even continents.
He also stressed that, while this is admirable, the response of Western European countries to the refugee crisis is not adequate.
“It is impossible for everyone to come to Europe,” he said in his speech.
Although the Dalai Lama praised the actions taken by Germany and Austria in connection with the crisis, he stressed that this is only a temporary solution.
“Taking care of thousands of refugees is fine, but at the same time you have to think about long-term solutions, how to bring real peace and real development, mainly through education, to these Muslim countries,” he said.
After all, we have to think about how to reduce the number of murders in their countries.
We must reduce the use of force.
The use of force has never solved these problems,” he added.
Speaking about the violence, the Dalai Lama also commented on George W. Bush’s actions following the 9/11 attacks, saying that the U.S.’s harsh response has set off a chain of uncontrollable events.
After 9/11, I expressed my condolences in a letter to President Bush and told him that a solution to this problem is possible through non-violence.
I know his intentions were good, but he used force, and it caused unexpected consequences,” the Dalai Lama said.
Fourfold increase in the number of children who have swallowed hand sanitizer in the past 4 years
Toxicology centers in the United States have reported a nearly 400 percent increase since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who have swallowed a high-alcohol hand sanitizer, according to the Georgia Toxicology Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Toxicology Center, cases of children under the age of 12 ingesting hand sanitizer fluids reported to toxicology centers increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children are more likely to come into contact with these substances, and unfortunately, some percentage of them go to the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
He said some children drink disinfectant on purpose, and some do so to impress their friends, or to argue for social media.
Youtube videos show teenagers drinking disinfectant liquid as cheap booze.
The teens reportedly mixed the disinfectant liquid with an alcohol-containing mouthwash to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the pleasant smells of disinfectant liquid.
“The child doesn’t think it could hurt him,” Lopez said.
Many of the most attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are flavored.
There are hand sanitizers with the smell of strawberries, grapes, oranges, which are very attractive for children.
Hand sanitizer contains anywhere from 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
In young children, in particular, only a few sprays can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s high-concentration alcohol,” said Dr. Stephen Thornton, chief physician at the Toxicology Center at the University of Kansas Hospital.
You wouldn’t just leave a glass of whiskey, but people keep these hand sanitizers in mind, and if kids get to them, it’s a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Naija Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently at school swallowed a strawberry-flavored hand sanitizer in the amount of about four sprays, was sent for treatment to the emergency room.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice that of an adult who is legally considered to be intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, an emergency physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta.
Naija was confused and unable to walk when she was taken to the emergency room.
Doctors watched her all night in a separate children's clinic, so as not to miss any signs of brain injury, because of alcohol, the girl fell and hit her head, said Ritchie.
"It was very scary," Ortoria Scott, Naiji's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic substances or disinfectant wipes, in addition to removing hand sanitizers from children’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants are associated with death.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing a disinfectant containing a toxic undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a deadly agent, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as an active substance.
In January, three fourth-graders in northern New York conspired to poison their "opposing" teacher by "spreading antibacterial substances in the classroom," according to a police report.
The teacher has a severe allergy to hand sanitizers, and she has forbidden to keep them in her class.
Police believe the failed plan was "empty talk", and address discipline issues to the school district.
As the oldest children's library in Barnaul became a family club.
On the back of the bench at the entrance to the regional children's library named after N.K. Krupskaya sad cast iron owl.
