Nadezhda Konstantinovna even once sent her childhood photo to distant Barnaul friends.
And when the Barnauls asked if Nadezhda Konstantinovna did not mind that the library was given her name, she wrote that she did not, does not mind.
The letters have long been dusting in the museum, and the grandchildren and great-grandchildren of the first readers have to explain whose harsh profile adorns the bas-relief on the library building.
During the years of perestroika, different people often called, indignant: why is the children’s library not renamed?
Let there be a library named after some good children's writer, without political coloring!
The library staff sat down, thought, and decided to leave everything as it is.
"Krupskaya" is perhaps the most famous and favorite library in Barnaul, as a "leninka" in Moscow.
On the floor in the library lobby is a yellow brick walkway.
"The Wizard of the Emerald City" is a favorite theme of the artist Oli Moskovka.
Previously, Olga was a manager in a law firm, came to work at eight, left at five, and all the other managers differed only in her love of drawing.
And then I found an ad on the Internet: "I need an illustrator for a book."
The book was written by a little American girl, and it was called "My Cancer Mommy" - "My mother has cancer."
Olga made illustrations, and thought: life can end at any moment, and there will be no miracles in it if you do not create them yourself.
Now she works in the library, illustrates children's books of writers around the world and writes fairy tales herself.
Traditionally, it is believed that children lose interest in the book, that they increasingly live in some kind of virtual space.
But reading children come to us, and their parents understand the meaning of reading, - says Tatyana Kushvid, director of the library.
In recent years, we have even had such a moment of confidence that the children's library is needed, and it will live - the kids are coming here!
I think my interest in reading is back.
In the lobby of the library hangs a large exhibition stained glass window with an updated photo exhibition.
Once a quarter, new photos of readers who go to the library with the whole family are posted: mom, dad and children.
The library is glad that with children more and more fathers began to come.
If in two years the child read all Chukovsky, then at an older age he needs books more complicated.
But now there is a law according to which an eight-year-old prodigy is forbidden to issue books from the category 12+.
To get such a book, the child must bring his parents with him - they come, then they come back again, and gradually "Krupskaya" becomes for them something like a family club.
The library has treasures - a pre-revolutionary collection of epics with verses and eras, the story of Korolenko in the annex to the magazine "Niva", the backing "Murzilki" for 1936.
