The Nobel Prize Winner: Globalization
The processes of globalization should have contributed to reducing inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in incomes in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, says Eric Maskin, chief researcher at the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of HSE Decisions, winner of the 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics.
Over the past 20 years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between countries have become increasingly open.
Proponents of globalization have predicted great benefits for developing economies.
“And these forecasts have largely come true,” says Maskin.
China and India, for example, have experienced strong GDP growth per capita.
But not everything is so rosy.
It was expected that globalization would reduce the gap between the “haves” and “have-nots” in poor countries, which is manifested in large income inequality, or rather, wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, says Eric Maskin in his article “Why global markets have not reduced inequality in developing economies”, published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by the HSE.
Together with the economist, Professor of Harvard University Michael Kremer Eric Maskin has developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why the income gap in poor countries increases with the growth of globalization, reminiscent of the HSE.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin allocates four skill levels - A and B for rich countries, C and D - for the poor.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries lack the skill level to collaborate with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And if C-level workers from poor countries have higher wages thanks to cooperation with B-level workers from rich countries, then D-level workers do not feel growth or their wages are falling at all.
The net effect is that the internationalization of production will contribute to the widening of the wage gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and, consequently, to increasing the level of inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
It allows us to explain why globalization has led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, ordinary professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Decisions, head of the HSE Department of Mathematics.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the means to do this, and it is unprofitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role, Maskin said.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no case calls for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bearing fruit in the form of GDP growth of countries.
Derbent: The Living Link of Time.
Derbent - one of the oldest cities in Russia - in September celebrates its 2000th anniversary.
The program of festive events includes a festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and a fair in the style of past times, an exhibition of Derbent carpets and the Day of Open Temples, a historical and musical show "2000 years in two hours" and excursions to the reconstructed Peter I Museum.
Medieval stones of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, ancient Arabic inscriptions on the walls, narrow streets and palace gardens - all this seems to have come down from the pages of "One Thousand and One Nights".
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has been preserved in its place since ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, the Khazar Khanate and the Golden Horde.
The age of the eastern plantains, which grow in the courtyard of the Derbent Juma Mosque, is equal to several centuries.
These powerful plants are protected by the All-Russian program "Trees - monuments of wildlife".
The shadow of the scattered crowns saves pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
The visitor of the mosque will be poured with fragrant tea and treated with Dagestani delicacies - honey figs, persimmons, mushmula, miracle cakes, ayran and sweets.
In Derbent, from time immemorial, large samovars have been used to give tea to numerous guests at one time.
An inscription above the entrance to the Juma Mosque says that the building was built in the year 115 AH.
That is, in the year 733 according to the Gregorian calendar.
It is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is striking in scope and solemnity: arcades of domes and vaults rely on square columns and are illuminated by rays of the sun from tiny windows.
The maintenance and breeding of pigeons is a traditional hobby of the inhabitants of Derbent.
Owners of domestic birds put doves in yards, under trees, in attics.
An exciting sight is the rise into the sky of a flock of white pigeons, similar to flashes of festive fireworks.
In order to defend against the enemy, the ancient Persians blocked the Caspian Gate with a double stone wall.
Leaving for 500 meters into the sea, this structure locked the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets in Derbent were woven in the 5th century, and to this day the technology of this unique craft has remained almost unchanged.
In one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets are sold for every taste - strips of wool, cotton or felt of all colors and shades, with a pile and without it, with complex ornamentation and a whimsical border.
The development of the city began with magals - blocks with one-story stone buildings.
Over the years, the magi have hardly changed.
Only satellite dishes, air conditioners on the walls and street lamps remind you that you are not in a medieval, but in a modern city.
In the old part of the city, the details of the water supply system built by the Persians about a thousand years ago have been preserved.
To this day, ancient sources have survived, in which local residents still collect water today.
Many Derbent people prefer ordinary tap water to water from proven historical fountains.
In Derbent was one of the centers of pottery.
Watering and painted vases, dishes, jugs, cups were valued throughout the Caucasus.
The hands of potters and now make wonderful ceramic products for both practical and souvenir purposes.
On the days of holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under a tight rope, which is performed by students of the Republican School of Circus Art.
The history of amazing and risky craftsmanship dates back several centuries.
A new trend - among the ropewalkers more and more often you can see girls.
In the premises of the former Maiden's bath today there is a museum "Culture and life of Ancient Derbent".
Previously, unmarried girls and brides were washed here, accompanied by friends, and now anyone can see the vaulted-dome hall, hot and cold pools, bathing accessories that have gone into the past.
Most Derbent houses have hot water, but baths and steam rooms are as popular today as they were in the old days.
The benefits of warming up the body with steam are written in ancient books.
After the bath, blood improves, muscles lose fatigue, the body acquires flexibility and lightness.
The festival "Commonwealth", which takes place on the territory of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, is attended by ethnopodvory of many districts of Dagestan.
Participants in national costumes dance, play folk melodies, sing songs of the peoples of the Caucasus and treat visitors with delicious homemade cheese.
Kirkhlyar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid their heads for Islam.
This is one of the most revered complexes for Muslims of the North Caucasus.
The sarcophagus, yellowed from time, is carved from solid stone blocks and oriented, as is customary among Arabs, along the axis of the west-east.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubov cut and shave customers in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
The barbershop has been in this place for many years.
Receptions of the barber craft are passed on from generation to generation.
At the same time, the Yakubov brothers can make not only traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old Town, the house in which the exiled writer-decembrist Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinsky lived lived.
Having learned the Turkic language and collected ethnographic material, he described Derbent of the first third of the 19th century with its ancient monuments, life and everyday life of citizens.
Chaihana is a traditional club of the East, where only tea and homemade pastries are served.
Men come here to quench their thirst, communicate with friends and solve some work problems.
As in the past, women are not recommended to cross the threshold of tea.
The Derbent dance ensemble "Caspian" was created three years ago, but already managed to take part in events of the republican and Russian level.
The soloists of the ensemble rehearse every day, learning to perfection the folk avar, dargin, tat, Armenian dances.
With the onset of the evening, when the noise subsides and street lights are lit, local residents sit on benches near houses with protruding terraces.
As a rule, Derbents discuss domestic issues.
But on the eve of the anniversary, they increasingly recall episodes of the unique history of their city, which influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
